Filter out the low quality data

pbmc.obj <- subset(pbmc.obj, subset = nFeature_RNA > 200 & nFeature_RNA < 2500 & percent.mt < 5)

#Normalizing the data A global-scaling normalization method LogNormalize that normalizes the feature expression measurements for each cell by the total expression, multiplies this by a scale factor (10,000 by default), and log-transforms the result.

pbmc.obj <- NormalizeData(pbmc.obj, normalization.method = "LogNormalize", scale.factor = 10000)
## Normalizing layer: counts
#pbmc.obj <- NormalizeData(pbmc.obj)

#Identification of highly variable features (feature selection) We next calculate a subset of features that exhibit high cell-to-cell variation in the dataset (i.e, they are highly expressed in some cells, and lowly expressed in others).

pbmc.obj <- FindVariableFeatures(pbmc.obj, selection.method = "vst", nfeatures = 2000)
## Finding variable features for layer counts

#Scaling the data Next, we apply a linear transformation (scaling) that is a standard pre-processing step prior to dimensional reduction techniques like PCA. The ScaleData() function:

Shifts the expression of each gene, so that the mean expression across cells is 0 Scales the expression of each gene, so that the variance across cells is 1 This step gives equal weight in downstream analyses, so that highly-expressed genes do not dominate The results of this are stored in pbmc[[RNA]]$scale.data By default, only variable features are scaled. You can specify the features argument to scale additional features

all.genes <- rownames(pbmc.obj)

Scaling data

##Heatmap of top 5 genes DoHeatmap() generates an expression heatmap for given cells and features. In this case, we are plotting the top 5 markers for each cluster.

pbmc.markers %>%
    group_by(cluster) %>%
    dplyr::filter(avg_log2FC > 1) %>%
    slice_head(n = 5) %>%
    ungroup() -> top5
